    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 12/80</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>If you will read Häckels “Evolution of Man”—if this Translation has appeared in America, or his Schöpfungsgesikter—and my Descent of Man, I think that you will find reference to everything important.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.3 will] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘you’ </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Ferguson had asked for a list of books on ‘the theory of evolution as relating to man’ (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 27,<ref target="./DCP-LETT-12371.xml"> letter from C. E. Ferguson, 27 December 1879</ref>). The US edition of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2048.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Haeckel’s</ref> <hi rend="italic">Natürliche Schöpfungsgeschichter</hi> was published by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_135.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Appleton &amp; Co</ref>mpany in 1880 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11061.xml">Haeckel 1880</ref>). <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1969.xml"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d US ed.</ref> was also published by Appleton.</note>
            
            
        </div>
    
